spec: ab3301
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__ dict-presence (in-place /=, //=, %=) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__itruediv__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __itruediv__. In-place true division (__itruediv__, /=) is the augmented assignment variant of __truediv__. abc types define no __truediv__ (confirmed false in wave 659), so __itruediv__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic semantics — ABC /= n is not a defined Python operation and ABC has no __itruediv__. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve in-place division. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __itruediv__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not numeric or arithmetic types. f /= n is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__ifloordiv__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ifloordiv__. In-place floor division (__ifloordiv__, //=) is the augmented assignment variant of __floordiv__. abc types define no __floordiv__ (confirmed false in wave 659), so __ifloordiv__ is equally absent. abc.ABC has no numeric data model; ABC //= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; in-place floor division is entirely absent. The function type does not define __ifloordiv__; f //= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "Key finding (__imod__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __imod__. In-place modulo (__imod__, %=) is the augmented assignment variant of __mod__. abc types define no __mod__ (confirmed false in wave 659), so __imod__ is equally absent. Note: str defines __mod__ for % string formatting, but abc types are not str subclasses and implement no formatting protocol. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no sequence, numeric, or in-place arithmetic data model. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; %= has no meaning for metaclass objects. The function type does not define __imod__; f %= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 666 (__iadd__/__isub__/__imul__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place augmented assignment dunder tested across 16 consecutive waves (652–667). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __itruediv__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__itruediv__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __itruediv__.
# In-place true division (__itruediv__, /=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __truediv__. abc types define no __truediv__ (wave 659), so __itruediv__
#   is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic
#   or numeric semantics. ABC /= n is not a defined Python operation; ABC has
#   no __itruediv__ to serve as an implementation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. In-place division has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __itruediv__. f /= n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no
#   arithmetic or in-place augmented assignment data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3301.itruediv:
  description: "abc types __itruediv__ dict-presence checks; wave 667"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3301

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3301001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__itruediv__"], false]
    - ["ab3301002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__itruediv__"], false]
    - ["ab3301003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__itruediv__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ifloordiv__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ifloordiv__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ifloordiv__.
# In-place floor division (__ifloordiv__, //=) is the augmented assignment
#   variant of __floordiv__. abc types define no __floordiv__ (wave 659),
#   so __ifloordiv__ is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: no numeric or arithmetic data model; ABC //= n is not a defined
#   Python expression. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no
#   state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __ifloordiv__ for in-place floor division.
#   ABCMeta's API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__)
#   has no arithmetic or augmented assignment component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ifloordiv__. f //= n is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to
#   its role as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3301.ifloordiv:
  description: "abc types __ifloordiv__ dict-presence checks; wave 667"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3301

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3301004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ifloordiv__"], false]
    - ["ab3301005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ifloordiv__"], false]
    - ["ab3301006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ifloordiv__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __imod__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__imod__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __imod__.
# In-place modulo (__imod__, %=) is the augmented assignment variant of __mod__.
# abc types define no __mod__ (wave 659), so __imod__ is equally absent.
# Note: str defines __mod__ for % string formatting, but abc types are not str
#   subclasses and implement no sequence-repetition or formatting protocol.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper with no sequence, numeric, or
#   in-place arithmetic data model. ABC %= n is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading. ABCMeta %= n is not a valid Python
#   expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __imod__. Unlike str, which uses __mod__ for %
#   formatting, CPython's built-in function type has no __imod__. f %= n is
#   not a valid Python expression for callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3301.imod:
  description: "abc types __imod__ dict-presence checks; wave 667"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3301

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3301007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__imod__"], false]
    - ["ab3301008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__imod__"], false]
    - ["ab3301009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__imod__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __itruediv__: false for all 3.
# __ifloordiv__: false for all 3.
# __imod__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 666 (__iadd__/__isub__/__imul__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__,
#          __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__, __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place
#   augmented assignment operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, reflected, and augmented assignment dunder tested across 16
#   consecutive waves (652–667). Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, reflected bitwise
#   logical, or in-place augmented assignment protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

